{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16739"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16739"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.27,0.34,0.1,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90230"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9430"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74476"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1396"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"},{"type":"tags","id":"9006"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30646"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90230"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of unilateral nasal obstruction and occasional epistaxis. He reports facial pain and numbness over his right cheek. He has noticed a 5 kg weight loss over this period despite no change in appetite. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has worked as a cabinet maker for 35 years. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a firm mass visible in the right nasal cavity. There is reduced sensation in the distribution of the right maxillary nerve. A CT scan reveals an expansile mass in the right nasal cavity extending into the maxillary sinus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymphoma","Esthesioneuroblastoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Inverted papilloma","Adenocarcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation and occupational history strongly suggest adenocarcinoma of the nasal cavity. The unilateral nature of symptoms, progressive nasal obstruction, epistaxis and constitutional symptoms are classic presenting features. The presence of facial numbness in the distribution of the maxillary nerve (V2) is particularly concerning as it suggests perineural invasion or direct tumour extension, which is characteristic of malignant processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses has a strong association with wood dust exposure, with relative risks reported to be up to 900 times higher in wood workers compared to the general population. The latency period between exposure and cancer development is typically decades. The patient\u0027s 35-year history as a cabinet maker represents significant cumulative exposure. The combination of unilateral symptoms, maxillary nerve involvement, and occupational exposure makes this diagnosis most likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common type of sinonasal malignancy overall but lacks the strong association with wood dust exposure seen in adenocarcinoma. The absence of smoking history and presence of significant occupational exposure makes adenocarcinoma more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInverted papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign but locally aggressive tumour that can undergo malignant transformation. While it can present similarly, it lacks the strong occupational association seen here and typically does not cause neurological symptoms until very advanced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEsthesioneuroblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically arises from the olfactory epithelium in the upper nasal cavity and is not associated with occupational exposures. It usually presents with anosmia and tends to spread superiorly rather than involving the maxillary nerve distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in the sinonasal tract but is uncommon. While it can cause B symptoms such as weight loss, it lacks the specific occupational association seen with adenocarcinoma and rarely causes perineural invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wood dust exposure is a significant occupational risk factor for adenocarcinoma of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.","A detailed occupational history is essential when evaluating patients with sinonasal malignancies.","Early symptoms of sinonasal malignancy can be non-specific and may mimic chronic sinusitis.","Numbness in the distribution of the maxillary nerve suggests perineural invasion or local tumour spread."],"references":["Alonso-Sard\u00f3n M, Chamorro Antonio-J, Hern\u00e1ndez-Garc\u00eda I, Iglesias-de-Sena H, Mart\u00edn-Rodero H, Herrera C, et al. Association between Occupational Exposure to Wood Dust and Cancer: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Zhang Z, editor. PLOS ONE. 2015 Jul 20;10(7):e0133024.\u200c Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26191795/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74476"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74476"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-12T22:25:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T22:27:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9430"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90230"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"it